ed","–Female":"Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1177–Male":"1177–Deceased","1203–1256":"1203–1256","1120–1150":"1120–1150","1127–Female":"1127–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","1127":"1127","1203":"1203","ABT 1176":"about 1176","1256":"1256","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","ABT 1149":"about 1149","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toldedo, New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pérez","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Francisco, Pedro, Miguel, Jorge, Ramon, Rafael, Mario.","Spanish (<b>Pérez</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Pedro</i>, an equivalent of   Peter  . This surname is also found in France. Compare   De Perez  .","Breton (<b>Pérez</b>): variant of <b>Pérès</b> (see   Peres  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Parez","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Pérez</b> (see   Perez  ).","Czech (<b>Pařez</b>): nickname from <i>pařez</i> ‘(tree) stump’.","In some cases possibly also French (Nord), Walloon, and Flemish: variant of <b>Paré</b> (see   Pare  ) or   Paret  ."]},{"name":"Peter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Ernst, Fritz, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Kaspar, Klaus, Siegfried, Wolfgang.","English, Scottish, German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), Czech (Moravian), Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian; Hungarian (<b>Péter</b>): from the personal name <i>Peter</i> (Greek <i>Petros</i>, from <i>petra</i> ‘rock’). The personal name was popular throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, having been bestowed by Christ as a byname on the apostle Simon bar Jonah, the brother of Andrew. The name was chosen by Christ for its symbolic significance (John 1:42, Matt. 16:18); Saint Peter is regarded as the founding head of the Christian Church in view of Christ's saying, ‘Thou art Peter and upon this rock I will build my Church’. In Christian Germany in the early Middle Ages this was the most frequent personal name of non-ancient Germanic origin until the 14th century. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Czech   Petr  , Polish <b>Piotr</b> and <b>Pietr</b>, Albanian <b>Pjetri</b> (from the personal name <i>Pjetër</i>, definite form <i>Pjetri</i>), and also their derivatives (see examples at   Peterson  ). It has also been adopted as a surname by Ashkenazic Jews."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toledo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Jorge, Manuel, Ramon, Rafael, Juan, Antonio, Jesus, Miguel, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from the city in central Spain, which was the capital of the Visigothic state between the 6th and 8th centuries. Its role declined for three centuries after the Muslim invasion of Spain, until it was taken as the capital of the kingdom of Castile between the 11th and 16th centuries. It was a major cultural and political center throughout the Middle Ages, and was also the home of an important Jewish community. The placename, first recorded in Latin as <i>Toletum</i>, is of obscure etymology, possibly connected with <i>Toleto</i> in Piedmont; Jewish tradition connects it with Hebrew <i>toledot</i> ‘generations’, but this is no more than folk etymology. Compare   Toledano  .","Jewish (Sephardic): also an adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the surname their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Toledano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shlomo, Igal, Moshe, Shimon, Ehud, Shmuel, Yehuda.  Spanish Alberto, Gonzalo, Alina, Carlos, Conrado, Elena, Enrique, Evelia, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Ramona.  French Gabrielle, Michel.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Toledo (see   Toledo  ), from an adjectival form of the placename."]}]},{"name":"Gutier","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Antoine, Francois, Marcel, Pascale, Philippe, Remy, Thierry.  Spanish Jose, Jorge, Miguel, Adelina, Altagracia, Ana, Andres, Arnaldo, Artemio, Augusto, Carlos, Edilberto.","French: variant of   Gauthier  . This surname is also found in Spain (mainly Cádiz) and in the Dominican Republic. Compare   Gootee  .","History: This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Gootee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Gautier  ."]},{"name":"Goucher","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by a ditch, drain, or stream, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘watercourse’ + <i>-ier</i>, synonymous with Middle English <i>atte Gote</i>. This type of topographic name with the <i>-(i)er</i> suffix was common in Sussex and Kent.","occupational name for a goat herd, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘goat’ + the suffix <i>-ier</i>."]},{"name":"Gauthier","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Walter</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354684,"age":43,"year":"1200","julianDay":2159351,"description":"The Christian territory controlled the Kingdoms of Aragon, Navarre, and Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Gutier Pérez de Toledo was born in New Castile, Spain as the son of Alcalde Mayor Pedro Gutiérrez Suarez and Mrsa Pérez. He married Mrsa Gutierre Perez about 1176, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1203–1256":"1203–1256","1120–1150":"1120–1150","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1127":"1127","1203":"1203","ABT 1176":"umbes 1176","1256":"1256","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","ABT 1149":"umbes 1149","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toldedo, New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Hispaania"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1177–Male":"1177–Kuollut","1203–1256":"1203–1256","1120–1150":"1120–1150","1127–Female":"1127–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170","1127":"1127","1203":"1203","ABT 1176":"noin 1176","1256":"1256","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","ABT 1149":"noin 1149","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Toldedo, New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Espanja"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Male":